      <h2 class="font-headline text-2xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-10 mb-4">Standard vs Anti-Static Bubble Wrap: The Key Distinction</h2>
      <p>The most important thing to understand about bubble wrap and electronics is the static electricity risk. Standard clear bubble wrap is made from polyethylene — a good electrical insulator. When you rub bubble wrap against plastic and electronic surfaces, it generates triboelectric static charges that can reach thousands of volts. For most consumer devices in their retail boxes, this is not a problem. For bare electronic components — circuit boards, processors, RAM modules, hard drives — even a small electrostatic discharge (ESD) can permanently damage sensitive components invisibly.</p>

      <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-semibold text-on-surface mt-6 mb-3">When Standard Bubble Wrap is Safe for Electronics</h3>
      <p>Standard bubble wrap is perfectly safe for packaging consumer electronics that are fully assembled and enclosed in their original casing — phones, laptops, monitors, TVs, cameras. The device's outer casing provides adequate ESD protection. The bubble wrap's job is purely mechanical cushioning against drops and impacts.</p>

      <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-semibold text-on-surface mt-6 mb-3">When You Need Anti-Static Bubble Wrap</h3>
      <p>Anti-static bubble wrap (usually pink or black) is required when packaging bare printed circuit boards (PCBs), memory modules, processors, open hard drives, graphics cards out of their box, or any electronic component without a protective outer casing. The conductive additives in anti-static film safely dissipate any static buildup. This is an industry standard in electronics manufacturing and component distribution.</p>

