      <h2 class="font-headline text-2xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-10 mb-4">Correct Bubble Wrap Technique for Electronics</h2>
      <p>The way you wrap matters as much as the type you choose. Common mistakes include wrapping too loosely (items shift inside the box), wrapping with bubbles on the outside rather than against the product, and using too few layers. For electronics, the bubbles should face inward — against the device surface — so they provide direct cushioning. Outer-facing bubbles provide less cushioning and more surface area for damage during handling.</p>

      <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-semibold text-on-surface mt-6 mb-3">The Box-in-Box Method for Fragile Electronics</h3>
      <p>For high-value electronics, the box-in-box method offers the best protection: place the bubble-wrapped device in a smaller inner box, then cushion that box inside a larger outer box with at least 5cm of void fill on all sides. This creates two layers of impact absorption and prevents direct penetration damage from drops or compressions.</p>

